stice. He reached Helena that July and held the bench until resigning in 1868.","number":1},{"category":"family","header":"His mother was Edwin Stanton's cousin","body":"Munson's mother was a cousin of Edwin Stanton, Lincoln's secretary of war, a tie that set him near the administration that sent him west. A Yale Law graduate of 1851, he had trained for the bench in New Haven.","number":2},{"category":"legacy","header":"He came home to New Haven for good","body":"After resigning the Montana bench in 1868, Munson settled back in New Haven where he had studied law. He died there in 1908 and lies in Grove Street Cemetery.","number":3}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM009"},"cross_connections":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Yale Law School","graduation_year":1851,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Lyman Ezra Munson","first_name":"Lyman","last_name":"Munson","middle_name":"Ezra","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1851"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"lyman-munson-1822"},"HD3015":{"id":"HD3015","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1868,"month":12,"day":27,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1947,"month":7,"day":7,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM044"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0570","mother_id":"X01243"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02053","children_ids":["HD3016"],"date_year":1893,"date_month":1,"date_day":1}],"number_of_marriages":1,"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","institution_blurb":"Yale School of Medicine, M.D. 1892; M.A. Yale 1893."},{"institution_id":"INST122"}],"tags":["physician","author","inventor","wwi","spanish_american_war","scientist"],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"HD0338","display_label":"Served as health officer for Manila under Governor Taft in 1903 — two Hooker descendants, one running the Philippines.","link_text":"William Howard Taft"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"HD3073","display_label":"Both were Bohemian Club members — two Hooker descendants in the same institution.","link_text":"Henry Waters Taft"}],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — Edward Lyman Munson","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Lyman_Munson"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military","medicine","science"],"notable_blurb":"Designed the Munson Last G.I. shoe 1912","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Lyman_Munson","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"He designed the G.I. shoe","body":"Munson spent four years studying the feet of 2,000 soldiers, then designed a shoe last — snug in heel and arch, with a roomy upturned toe. The Munson Last became U.S. military footwear from 1912 onward: the hobnail brogan of WWI and the G.I. shoe of WWII.","number":1},{"header":"He attended McKinley after the shooting","body":"Munson was one of the physicians who attended President McKinley in Buffalo after the assassination attempt on September 6, 1901. Two years later he served as health officer for Manila under Governor William Howard Taft — another Hooker descendant. He survived tuberculosis contracted in the Philippines, and in 1923 commanded American medical relief after the Great Kantō earthquake in Japan.","number":2}],"bio":{"display_name":"Brig. Gen. Edward Lyman Munson","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Munson","married_names":[],"middle_name":"Lyman","title":"Brigadier General","photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/111-SC-43476_-_NARA_-_55245945-c